SHALLOW WATER TRANSPARENCY (seeing the seabed through it) in a refraction+absorption water model: two non-obvious sources of a 'grey milky, not transparent' look, both downstream of a correct color model. (1) A surface-skin floor added to the optical path (path = depth/NoV + FLOOR) forces a fixed fraction of the scatter/deepColor veil over EVEN zero-depth water = a flat grey film on the seabed. Set FLOOR=0 so absorb=exp(0)=1 at zero depth -> body is pure refraction (seabed shows through, transparent); the scatter veil then builds only with real depth. (2) A per-water exposure boost (wcol*=1.2) + ACES + gamma lifts a mid-value water body up the gamma curve into a pale wash -- drop the boost on the water path (keep it on terrain). Also DIM the refracted seabed (refrCol*~0.55) so it reads as 'seen underwater' AND sits below the gamma blow-out band. Net recipe that worked: waterBody = refrCol*0.55*absorb + deepColor*(1-absorb), absorb=exp(-sigma*depth/NoV) with sigma~(0.16,0.05,0.02) red-first and NO path floor, no *1.2 on water. Validated by center-pixel: milky (209,223,219 near-equal) -> teal (137,172,165 channel-spread) + screenshot showing shallow seabed-through transparent -> deep blue gradient.